properties.name: Coco La Ti Da
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey806 East Roy Street, 98102A potential "favorite". Only been once for desert, but it was great. Cool/modern atmosphere. Nice staff. Want to go back to try the food. OK, bad review in the paper on the food, so maybe I\'ll stick with desert. Guess that they almost closed - more people need to go for desert.

properties.name: Crow Restaurant
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 823 Fifth Ave. N, SeattleAnother favorite. Always tough deciding between chicken and lasagne, however the chicken could be best I\'ve ever had.

properties.name: Dandelion
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 5809 24th Ave. N.W, Seattle, WAOne of our favorite restaurants. Great neighborhood spot.

properties.name: Divino
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey5310 Ballard Ave NW, 98107Modern, Italian wine bar. Good place for a light meal and some wine. Big contrast to other local Portalis, but both are great. Depends on your mood. Portalis is more laid back but Divino has a much larger menu. Service has been inconsistent.

properties.name: El Greco
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 219 Broadway ave E, seattle waOur favorite place for breakfast/brunch.

properties.name: Kisaku
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 2101 N. 55th St, 98103Great sushi spot, probably top 3 in Seattle along with Nishino and Shiros.

properties.name: Lark Restaurant
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 926 12th Avenue, Seattle, WA, 98122Chosen as Seattle\'s best restaurant by Seattle Magazine. Not sure if I\'d go that far, but it\'s good and I normally don\'t like "small plates" restaurants.

properties.name: Matt's in the Market
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 94 pike, 98101One of our first Seattle dining experiences. Hidden gem in the heart of tourist area where no tourists dine - unless you ask the info booth person "where do the locals eat around here?". Anyway, I just saw Matt\'s blog which details their new expansion - they\'ll actually have a kitchen. Anyway, our favorite is lunch - the catfish sandwich is tasty.

properties.name: Monsoon
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey  615 19th Ave E, Seattle, WAWe tried this place when we lived in Capitol Hill and the wait was too long at Kingfish (which we ultimately didn\'t like that much) across the street. Service is consistently inconsistent, but the food is always great. Must get the spicy drunken chicken (you can get this in sandwich form at their sandwich shop - Baguette Box - in south Capitol Hill) and most of the vegetable dishes are good too (although we didn\'t love the green beans). Whenever we see Eric we beg for him to put the seafood chow mein back on the dinner menu. We keep meaning to try their dim sum brunch.

properties.name: Nishino
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey   3130 East Madison Street, Seattle, WA, 98112Probably our favorite sushi restaurant in Seattle. Shiro\'s is also good, but decor is pretty stark there - just a more comfortable/warm feeling here. However, we probably go more to Kisaku (in Tangletown) now purely due to convenience. Not surprising but be prepared to drop 0 per person.

properties.name: Osteria La Spiga
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 1429 12th ave e, 98122Our standby for Italian. Almost always get the tagliatelle al ragu. Recently moved into a great new spot, although it\'s much larger so the feel is less intimate and I think they are still working out the kinks in terms of the staff/service of a larger place. Also, parking is now much more of a challenge. We just tried Tavolata and think that La Spiga now has a rival for Italian in Seattle.

properties.name: Portalis
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 5205 Ballard Ave NW, 98107Really a wine bar with a little food. Very warm feel. Staff is great and they allow dogs!

properties.name: Tavolata
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 2323 Second Avenue, Seattle, WAA bona fide alternative to La Spiga for authentic Italian in Seattle. Opened by Union chef Ethan Stowell after a few years of anticipation, but it was definitely worth the wait. Octopus salad and minestrone are amazing. Pastas are all great. Haven\'t had the guts to try the veal brain ravioli. I\'ve never seen donuts for desert in Italy, but hey they\'re good.

properties.name: Via Tribunali
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 913 E Pike St, 98122Authentic italian pizza. Really good and always packed. Heard they are opening another location with a more expansive menu on Queen Anne.

properties.name: Wild Ginger
properties.description: Posted by Gshuey 1401 3rd Avenue, Seattle, WA, 98101Probably Seattle\'s signature restaurant. Gotta have the duck and string beans. Seems like the service at the reception desk is always bad, but the wait service has really improved. Rarely get bad service now, however we usually just head into the bar where the staff turnover has been much lower.
